SYMPTOM_TEXT: I received the COVID-19 booster shot at 4:00pm on 12/2/21. At first, I was perfectly fine, with only a little fatigue and a headache. However, I woke up at 5am on 12/3/21 and felt my heart racing and my stomach hurting. I got up to go get some water, and almost collapsed ~15 feet into my walk. I was able to get help and drink some water, but the feeling didn't really go away. Once I was fully awake at 8am, I had an eye doctor's appointment at 9:30am. I was still unsteady when I went through the exam, and when waiting for dilation drops to kick in, I started feeling like I was going to throw up. I made my way to the restroom as quickly as possible, but collapsed before I reached the door (in the waiting room). My mother tried to lift me, but I was  basically a "ragdoll" as she tried. I had to be helped into the bathroom, where I threw up 3 or so times, partially some bile. After throwing up I felt better, but not perfect.  In addition to these episodes, I also experienced fatigue, headaches, chills, sweating, slight chest pain, arm soreness, and sore muscles (other than my arm). It has been 24 hours since the booster, and I still am having some of these symptoms in varying levels.
HISTORY: POTS (Postural Orthostatic Tachycardia Syndrome) IBS (Irritable Bowel Syndrome) Endometriosis (? - Currently suggested but not diagnosed yet)
PRIOR_VAX: I once almost collapsed after receiving the meningitis and flu shot (got at the same time)
ALLERGIES: Pediazole (infant ear infection medication) -- Got rash

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient discharged after (4) day inpatient admission. 11/27-12/1/21 Patient readmitted 12/2/2021.  current H & P and plan. Patient is a 77 y.o. male past medical history significant for CAD s/p stent placement, ICM, ESRD on HD, PAF on Eliquis, GI bleed, HTN, HLD, IDDM, OSA and recent hospitalization 11/27-12/1 for COVID pneumonia discharged home on continuous 2L oxygen. The patient presented to the ED today with worsening generalized weakness requiring more care/assistance at home than his wife can provide.  Since the patient was discharged yesterday he has been mainly lying in his bed at home. He hasn't been eating much or taking his medications. PT/OT had evaluated him during his hospitalization recommending home with assistance. The patient denies worsening SOB or cough. Denies fever, chills, chest pain, diarrhea, or vomiting. He is supposed to be on 2L oxygen continuously and 4L oxygen with ambulation.   11/27 admission hospital stay details: Pt is a 77 yr old M with PMHx of CAD s/p PCI, ICMP, ESRD on HD, PAF on Eliquis, Hx of GI bleed, HTN, HPL, IDDM II, and OSA presented to ED on 11/26 with AMS. Per his wife, he started feeling ill on 11/17-11/18 with cough, weakness, fevers, and diarrhea. Found to be COVID positive on 11/20 at Hospital.  Admitted for Encephalopathy due to COVID-19, ESRD/uremia, HTN Urgency, COVID 19 PNA, IDDM II. Found to have volume overload in the setting of missed HD. Nephrology was consulted and he had several hemodialyses with fluid removal which helped. He will restart hemodialysis on TTS on 12/2/21 due to positive COVID-19. Encephalopathy was felt to be due to volume overload and COVID-19 Pneumonia. Encephalopathy resolved.  Due to COVID-19 he had worsening hypoxia, he was initially on 2L NC but later transitioned to Ventimask. At the time of discharge, he was on O2 2 l/min and home O2 was arranged. He was initially treated with Decadron and was switched to IV Solumedrol 40 mg bid on 11/29. He was discharged home on Decadron 6 mg PO daily for 5 more days. Due to worsening hypoxia, he was pan-cultured and all cultures were negative except one which was positive for Staph. Epid. Which was contamination. He had empiric IV Rocephin/Doxycycline for 3 days, will continue 2 more days after discharge.  Repeat CXR on 12/1 showed improving infiltrate. He is out of isolation. He was discharged home on O2 2 l/min at rest and 4 l/min with activity. He also had hypertensive urgency on admission, which resolved. During hospitalization, his BP was on the low side. He was discharged home on Imdur and Norvasc. Procardia was stopped. Limited Echo 11/29 showed: Mild global hypokinesis with more prominent anteroseptal and apical wall motion abnormality. EF 43%, it was 45% on 03/14/2021. Regarding he was seen . HbA1c of 11.7. Will discharge home on Lantus 20 units QAM and Humalog 4 units for a full meal (50-60 grams carbs) or 2 units for a small meal (30 grams carbs) plus correction 1:85>150 while on Decadron. Once he stops Decadron may restart Lantus 10 units qhs. Baqsimi to use in the setting of severe hypoglycemia. Advise close follow up Center for Diabetes and Endocrinology and/or PCP. Per Dr.  consult note 3/29: The patient again will be counseled on the necessity for direct oversight and his wife has continued to verbalize her inability to help in his medical care.  The patient would do best by moving toward assisted living or 24-hour care to minimize acute issues in the future. If going home without the supervision of insulin dosing would be at risk of reoccurring blood glucose management issues/safety concerns. PT/OT recommended Home with an assist, home PT/O, and nursing. The patient was discharged home on 12/1/2021 only to be readmitted for weakness, fatigue.

I reconstituted and administered the dose. When I went to record the administration, the expiration date was not consistent with mfc storage guidelines. We had received the shipment initially, sent to a neighboring pharmacy, and returned to our site. The BUD for our supply we sent to the other pharmacy was expected by unspecified date. The plastic bag from the other pharmacy indicated 12/29/21, thirty days from the date it was sent back. I called the pharmacy it was sent from and was told it came out of the freezer. Unless the supply had been received from another source, this supply had been refroze. I discovered that was the case and reached out to the manufacturer and patient. Pfizer representatives had no data on this type of excursion. I reached out to Dept of Health and was referred to CDC guidance on administration errors and deviations. The clinical decision was made to repeat the dose at the patient's earliest convenience, once we could procure viable vaccine.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient ( 4/12/1958) presented to vaccination site on 12/01/2021. The client notified RN and other RN that she received two doses of Pfizer vaccine on 4/9/2021 and 4/30/21. Client requested to receive Moderna booster instead of Pfizer booster. Client reports that she experienced vomiting upon receiving first dose of Pfizer vaccine. Client reports experiencing diarrhea upon receiving second dose of vaccine. Both symptoms lasted one day. At three weeks post vaccination client followed up with primary care provider where thyroid labs where drawn. Client reports that TSH levels were elevated and primary care provider prescribed levothyroxine. In July/August the client developed a diverticulitis flare up. The client has a history of diverticulitis 5 years ago. Client denies any other significant medical history, no allergies, no previous history of a reaction to a vaccine. RN and RN submitted a medical consult via text message to Vaccine Operations Leads requesting to proceed with the COVID vaccine Moderna booster. Per CDC guidance, approval to proceed with Moderna booster was obtained from medical consult team via text message, Vaccine Operations Lead. Client received COVID vaccine booster Moderna Lot 027H21B. Client did not report any symptoms during the 30 minute observation period. RN educated client on possible adverse reactions and when to seek care. The client left the vaccination site in no apparent distress and unassisted.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient expired 12/1/21  following discharge from inpatient admission and transferred to hospice care.  Patient was admitted for (7) days 11/23-11/30/2021. Patient is an 82-year-old male with past medical history significant for AFib, hypertension, asthma/chronic obstructive pulmonary disease, type 2 diabetes, nonischemic cardiomyopathy, history of VFib status post ICD placement who presented to the emergency department with chief complaint of fatigue, fever and confusion.  In the emergency department, patient was hypoxemic and placed on supplemental oxygen.  Chest x-ray revealed peripheral opacities.  Patient was positive for COVID-19.  Patient is vaccinated with Johnson & Johnson, no booster.  He was admitted to the Internal Medicine Service.  He was started on Decadron.  CT head was obtained which revealed no acute intracranial hemorrhage but with areas of age indeterminate regions of low attenuation potentially subacute an additional areas of age indeterminate mild small-vessel ischemic changes and a chronic appearing small infarct. Neurology was consulted.  Neurology felt findings were likely chronic cardioembolic infarcts that the patient likely has undiagnosed dementia, mixed type Alzheimer and vascular.  They recommended outpatient follow-up in the dementia clinic in 3 months. The patient had poor oral intake and a Corpak was placed and the patient was started on tube feeds. DGMS was consulted to help manage blood sugars. Palliative care was consulted for goals of care; the patient requested a meeting with hospice.. Family met with hospice and decided to discharge home with hospice. Xarelto stopped per family request. Discharged with oral morphine, haldol & ativan per hospice recommendations

Patient discharged after (31 hour ) admission. Patient was admitted for malaise, fatigue and Covid (+). He was put on oxygen intermittently, but walking sats stable 92-96. He was given MAB's, supportive care and improved the next day such that he felt well enough to go home. He was found to be persistently in atrial fibrillation; echo showed preserved EF, with no thrombus; Ziopatch was applied and he was advised to follow up with PCP concerning these results, as well as to discuss his understandable hesitancy with being on Eliquis, though he agrees to take it for now. He also has sutures in place on his left cheek, he wishes these to be removed, as he won't be able to enter his surgeon's office for this d/t Covid. They are removed without issue. He is discharged to home with his daughter, in stable condition.    New Medications: Eliquis 5mg twice daily.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I was preparing to draw up a Pfizer dose when I was called away to assist a patient at the register. I had already prepared the syringe to stick in into the vial by pulling in the correct amount of air when I was called away to assist a patient at the register. I proceeded to help that patient and went back to my vaccination. In my haste to get to the patient I grabbed the syringe that was full of air and administered it to the patient, not realizing I had not drawn up the vaccine. I immediately realized my mistake when I pushed the plunger and withdrew the needle. I apologized to the patient and explained my error and asked him if he would allow me to administer the vaccine. He was very understanding and he allowed me to inject him with his Pfizer dose.

With the first does, the left arm got sore immediately and never went away; just got worse.  It was swollen and red, and I hurt so bad I was basically screaming putting clothes on and off (for 3 days straight).  It started not hurting as tremendous on the 4th day, but continued to hurt for over 2 weeks.  Then 1-2 days after the shot, I started getting a rash all over my hands.  Doctors thought it was just me washing my hands so much due to 2 kids in diapers.  the 2nd-3rd day after the shot, I started getting some red rash and swollen eye lids (upper and lower). I went to my eye doctor and dermatologist but they couldn't figure anything out.  I couldn't do much else about it as had to take my baby up for open heart surgery over 3 hours away.  She was the priority.  Things got a tiny better when I was with her during her surgery recovery, but as soon as I came home (was up there for almost 2 weeks) everything got worse.  The eye lids were so red, swollen, itchy, and burned; it makes me look like a racoon but red instead of black.  My hands got worse and the rash is covering 1/3 of my hands.  It hurts, itches, and is dry; yet sometimes oozing.  I can't remember how long after the first vaccine, but after the second vaccine, I have a horrible itch in the crotch/growin area that never goes away unless I use extreme pressure and hot water from the shower head to make it go numb.
LAB_DATA: Eye doctor looked at eyes and couldn't figure anything out.  Dermatologist same thing; wants to do a skin patch test.  Primary care doctor won't call back after 4+ phone calls in 2 weeks
HISTORY: I have a TBI and mild asthma
ALLERGIES: Allergic to sulfa, latex, and cats

The patient reports that he began having symptoms on 11/20. He is vaccinated for COVID but has not had a booster. He has had poor appetite, chills, fevers, cough and shortness of breath as well as abdominal pain and diarrhea. His wife came down with symptoms on the same day. They believe he was exposed when he was sent to Hospital on 11/8 for follow up on his drop in hemoglobin. He had a pulse ox at home and was noting hypoxia in the 70's prompting him to come to ER for evaluation.    In the ER the patient was found to be hypoxic to 60% on room air on presentation. He quickly progressed to HFNC with a NRB mask due to being a mouth breather. He had labs showing significant elevation in BNP and D dimer. There was high clinical concern for PE however due to AKI a CTA thorax was unable to be obtained. Dopplers of upper and lower extremities obtained. He had an elevated procal and was started on antibiotics and had blood cultures ordered. The hospitalist team was contacted for admission and further management.   Of note the patient's daughter reports that his xarelto was stopped on 11/2 as his PCP noted a drop in hemoglobin to 12. He had his toe amputated last month and then had some epistaxis earlier this month and so the decision was made to stop the xarelto and continue to monitor. On Tuesday November 23 he said he noticed and felt a painful bump on ribs and he didn't tell us until about November 26. We discovered he had a visible lump on his ribs and couldn't feel anything else. It was painful to the touch and we weren't sure what it was. Saturday we looked at it again and it had multiplied to 4 going from his ribs into his armpit and we determined it was swollen lymph nodes. He is 45 pounds and 3 foot and skinny, so you could see them poking out of his skin so it was concerning because he had no other symptoms. We contacted the Doctor and she got us in to see on 12/01 and we saw her and she examined him and palpated him and found another lymph node on his neck on the left side and one in the armpit and we determined it was his lymph nodes. We did a CBC and all his blood work is normal and he has no symptoms of illness other than those lymph nodes. He does currently have a skin irritation called melasma and it's not irritated. No fever other than the lymph nodes being painful there was nothing else that would indicate he is sick, so that's where Doctor suggested we should still get the 2nd shot but we will do it on his right arm just incase and if he swells up we can determine if it's the vaccine. WBC was nice and low and within range and nothing out of range.

89 yo woman, very reliable historian, in generally good health except for some hypertension, high cholesterol but clear arteries (other than a widow-maker lesion found about 15 yrs ago from mild ssx and was by-passed succesfully) and an osteoporosis-related mid-thoracic vertebral fracture (3 years ago) causing a dowager?s hump becoming more prominent over time.   BPs controlled at 120/75 on enalapril 2.5 mg po q.am.  No other medications. PMH?at age 75 had successful but painful DaVinci bypass of ?widow-maker? lesion but all other coronaries were 100% patent. Gets no exercise. Sarcopenia to some extent. Non-obese (never was).  Age 84 had descending colon cancer, resected successfully and clear at 5 years without chemo.   First Moderna vaccine on 2/6/2021 (lot 030120A). Flu-like symptoms next 24-48 hours, better on tylenol.  Second Moderna vaccine on 3/6/2021 (lot 048821A). Flu-like symptoms next 24 hours, better on tylenol.  2 weeks later (~3/20/2021) had an episode of legs feeling funny or weak when she stood up.  Didn?t tell anyone, but it passed by the next day.  3/6/21 to 11/16/21: saw primary care doctor for checkup (07/14/2021). BP was 120/80 as it had been this whole time even at other doctor offices (saw ENT once and oncologist another time). No illnesses.  Third Modern vaccine on 11/16/2021 (lot 013F21A?lot # may have been transcribed to her vaccine card wrong?what?s the ?F? doing there?).  3 days later (11/19/2021) had episode of feeling unusual and with legs feeling weak progressing to arms. Here?s how it progressed. That day she went to put something in the gas oven (gas leak was ruled out the next day). But she felt like her legs were weak and she felt a bit light-headed so thought it wasn?t safe to bake. She turned off the oven. She carefully made her way about 10? to the dining room table, using her arms (and some legs) as support.  She then called 911. They told her to unlock her door (apartment 1200 sq-ft) that was about 20? away. She did, and as she moved from furniture to furniture piece, the weakness worsened and moved up to the arms also; and she felt more light-headed (?out of it?).  She unlocked the door and immediately sat in the rocking chair about 2 ? from the door. The paramedics arrived and found her conscious and alert but looking a little out of it. She was taken by ambulance to the hospital around the corner. In the ER, her BP was 280/120. They reflexively put her on IVFs (NS) and gave her I.V. hydralazine, which brough the BP down to about 190/100 or so, and she felt better. Seeing repeat BPs in the 190-210 range, they decided to keep her for overnight observation. They quadrupuled her dose of enalapril to 5.0 mg po BID (am and hs) in the hospital.  AFter the morning dose, her BP came down to about 190/90; at night it was about 185/80. She ended up staying, partly at my suggestion, for another 2 nights (3 days total stay).  The night and next day of admission, COVID was (-); Stroke and spinal impingement at the vertebral fracture site were ruled out, as were cardiopulmonary problems (ECG, CXR normal). And she could walk and had not felt light-headed since unlocking the apartment door.  And she wanted to go home the entire time (real pain in the neck).  In the hospital, PT & OT assessed her ability to walk, and she did great.  At d/c, her BP was 180/60, which they felt was OK, but it had been as low as 160/80 the preceding 24 hours (once).    She followed up with her PMD 8 days later (couldn?t get appt) and BP was 180/70, and noted this was indeed very high for her. So PMD continued enalapril at 5 mg po BID.   The episode never recurred nor has she felt light-headed.  My theory is that the spike protein this vaccine forces out bodies to produce is saturating the ACE (and probably other anti-Htn receptors).   So after the 3 doses of vaccine, each producing spike protein from the mRNA transcription (turns the body into a vaccine manufacturing facility, essentially), the spike protein progressively bound up more and more ACE and other anti-htn receptors.  On dose #2, It took 2 weeks of spike protein production to probably cause pretty high BP (never measured, but likely not as high as the 3rd dose), and that?s why she had a similar but lesser reaction 2 weeks after the 2nd dose.  Then after the 3rd dose, her ACE receptors were already pretty saturated, and it didn?t take much more spike protein production to bind up the ones that were left.  That?s likely why, on the 3rd dose, she suffered nearly malignant hypertension that made her feel light-headed and experience caudal to rostral weakness. Once the BP was lowered in the ER, she felt she could walk again, and through the hospital stay. And the doctor on the unit said that indeed, very high BP could cause exactly the reaction she had.  She remains on the 5 mg po BID enalapril dose and with BPs around 150-170/60-80.

He told me to take my medications and schedule an ECO gram on the 12/23/2021.  He also wanted me to get up and move around but not to over excert myself.  He also gave me a release to return to work.  I returned to work on 12/02/2021, still in discomfort but my symptoms seem to be lessoning as time goes by. Hospitalized (11.28.21);  COVID-19 positive (11.28.21); fully vaccinated  Admission Date: 11/28/2021 Discharge Date:  12/02/2021 Admission Diagnosis: AKI (acute kidney injury) Non-traumatic rhabdomyolysis Pneumonia due to COVID-19 virus Discharge Diagnosis:  AKI (acute kidney injury) Non-traumatic rhabdomyolysis  Pneumonia due to COVID-19 virus  Hospital Course: Patient is a 62 y.o. female with pmhx relevant for hypothyroidism, hyperlipidemia, obesity and arthritis who presented secondary to a chief complaint of severe fatigue.  She was vaccinated for COVID-19 and had no sick contacts.  She complained of worsening fatigue for 2 weeks prior to admission.  She was unable to get up from the floor after a fall.  She laid on the ground for 22 hours without moving.  Family brought her to the emergency department.  She admitted to decreased intake prior to admission.  In the emergency department, she was positive for COVID-19.  She had mild hypoxia and was placed on 2 L nasal cannula.  Chest x-ray showed left lower lobe opacity.  BMP showed a creatinine of 1.39 which was AKI.  She had an elevated CPK of 4300 from immobilization.  White count was 12000. Procalcitonin was mildly elevated.  She was treated with IV Rocephin and azithromycin for a 5 day course due to community-acquired pneumonia on top of COVID-19.  She was treated with fluids initially.  Her CPK and creatinine improved. She did receive dexamethasone for five days, discontinued at discharge. She is not a candidate for remdesivir due to time from onset of symptoms. PT/OT recommended skilled nursing facility at discharge however patient is adamant in her refusal to consider this despite discussion of risks/benefits. Husband works from home and is able to help care for her. Evaluated by pulmonary rehab and discharged with home oxygen 2L with exertion as well as home healthcare services.  Initial UA with RBC's however repeat one day prior to discharge without any hematuria.  Recommendations: CT head was performed due to a fall with possible head trauma.  There was no bleed or stroke noted.  There was concern for ventriculomegaly that was asymmetric.  MRI of the brain was ordered to further evaluate this which showed prominent lateral and third ventriculomegaly concerning for possible obstructing web / aqueductal stenosis vs hydrocephalus. She had no associated neurologic symptoms and this should be further evaluated as outpatient.   She had fairly significant hypokalemia which was repleted and I recommend repeat BMP in 1-2 weeks. Magnesium was also repleted.

On 15 Nov 2021, I received my Moderna Covid-19 booster.  I have concerns about how the vaccine was administered and its potential lack if efficacy.   The first thing that raised my concern during the vaccination was how slowly the vaccine administrator was pressing the syringe into my arm.  Second, after getting through my skin layer, the administrator had to apply additional force (while still pressing slowly) to get the needle into the muscle tissue.  Third, she slowly pressed the plunger to inject the vaccine into my arm.  Fourth, and most significant, when she pulled the needle from my arm, a significant amount of the vaccine was flowing down my arm from the injection site.  The injection  was one of (if not the most) uncomfortable injections I recall ever receiving.  Being concerned about the slow technique, I commented to vaccine administrator that I never recall having an injection done that slowly.  Her response was that her slow technique prevents or minimizes pain.    In the days following the booster injection, I did not experience the usual soreness around the injection site.  Prior to this booster during the 2021 calendar year, I received Moderna shots #1 and #2, shingles shots #1 and #2, and a flu shot.   All of them resulted in my arm being sore for a few days at the injection site.     Having seen much of the medication leak out when the needle was removed, I believe that the lack of soreness following the Moderna injection is evidence that an insufficient amount of the vaccine made it into my arm.    The most significant concern is that I do not believe that I received enough of the booster for it to do its job.   Given the possibly of not having received a sufficient amount, is it reasonably safe to simply repeat the booster to boost both my immunity and confidence?

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Note: I have no history of anxiety or panic attacks.  Roughly one week after the first dose, I had what was ultimately described as a panic attack - I went to the ER thinking it was a heart attack, where they did blood panels, x-ray, and a chest CT.  I was later discharged.  The problem recurred (but worse) the next day.  I have been chasing this ever since.  What happened - Six ish days after the first dose of Pfizer, I began having chest/abdomen pains, panic/anxiety problems.  Symptoms have lessened over time but returned later.  Symptoms - chest pain in middle-to-upper-left; panic/anxiety attacks began; unable to sleep many nights due to pain/constantly waking up with "impending doom" fears  What has been done - Four ER visits, several GP followups and lots of testing.  X-rays, chest/abdomen/pelvis CTs, blood panels, endoscopy and colonoscopy.  Diet changes.    All doctors (GP, ER) I've mentioned the timing to have mostly shrugged-off the timing with the vaccine, however, no other causes have been identified to-date, and the symptoms are still occurring - some days are better than others.  At this point, I'm wondering about the booster shot.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: At approximately 4:30am the morning after she received the second Pfizer dose, my daughter woke up with uncontrollable chills, fever and pain. She couldn't warm up. Her father picked her up from the dorm at approximately 6:30 am. She took fever lowering medicine and took a hot bath and still had chills. She then got in bed and laid under an electric blanket on high and finally fell back asleep. She woke up sweaty and feeling terrible with a sore throat, pain and fatigue. The fever and chills started back up again that afternoon. I also gave her aspirin as recommended. Various flulike symptoms dragged on for a week. She felt better for a few days the following week, then chills, low grade fever, lethargy and coughing started up again. She was affected for another week and into a third. During this time she visited our family practitioner, received the obligatory Covid test, negative. Doctor said her left ear looked red and also her throat had signs of inflammation. She was prescribed a three day dose anti-biotic, which did not help. My daughter also visited her health clinic, had her finger pricked and tested for flu, mono, anemia and Covid, all negative. They recommend more extensive bloodwork which she neglected to do and by the third week had recovered then within a week caught a cold.
LAB_DATA: flu, covis, anemia and mono tests

States that measured home temperatures were never elevated.  However, after the 1st few days post vaccination administration, patient reports worsening cough, shortness of breath and chest tightness that worsens with deep inspiration.  He reports intermittent sputum production which is yellow, denies presence of blood.  Patient does endorse that for the past 2 days he has been working on clearing land in building a new home, for which his shortness of breath and fatigue has been a hindrance to his work.  Patient's wife states that patient requested the route to the hospital when his chest tightness was severe in nature, given his cardiac history.  Patient's wife is fully vaccinated.  Patient states he is unaware of any known exposures.  He does not wear home oxygen.  Patient denies headaches, dizziness, abdominal pain, dysuria, hematuria, numbness or tingling in his extremities. In the emergency department patient was afebrile.  He was tachycardic and hypoxic requiring supplemental oxygen saturation.  Initially patient was started on 4 L via nasal cannula, at the time of our conversation he had been increased to 6 L via nasal cannula.  Pertinent lab findings include an elevated creatinine of 2.22.  BNP was within normal limits at 195. Troponins were within normal limits at 20 and then 21 at recheck.  EKG showed normal sinus rhythm.  Chest x-ray showed abnormal opacity in the left upper lobe extending from the hilum, abnormal patchy opacity in the retrocardiac left lung base.  Probable areas of left-sided pneumonia.  Suspect minimal strandy atelectasis in the right lung base as well.  Rapid COVID PCR was positive.  Due to concerns of acute respiratory failure with hypoxia secondary to COVID pneumonia, as well as acute kidney injury, patient was admitted to hospitalist service. Patient is a full code.  Discussed with patient our intention to admit to the hospital, which will include judicious fluid administration, and COVID treatment including Decadron and remdesivir.  I did discuss with patient and his wife at bedside his code status, and his comfort level with respiratory escalation should it be needed.  Patient is agreeable to are all respiratory intervention including mechanical intubation if needed.  Patient states he already feels better and would like to go home, at the encouragement and urging of his wife, patient agreed to stay to be admitted to undergo fluid administration and COVID treatment.  All questions and concerns answered at this time. Brief history and medical decision making:  51-year-old man with dilated cardiomyopathy type 2 diabetes, dyslipidemia and heart failure preserved ejection fraction, presented with shortness of breath.  Patient just received his 1st COVID vaccination and influenza vaccination 7 days ago.  Patient presented with cough sputum production and shortness of breath.  This is accompanied with worsening dyspnea on exertion.  In the emergency department he was hypoxemic and tachycardic.  Chest x-ray revealed left upper lobe opacification as well as patchy opacification in the left lung base.  Procalcitonin elevated.  COVID-19 positive.  Will start treatment for COVID-19 respiratory failure with superimposed bacterial community-acquired pneumonia.  Will start ceftriaxone/azithromycin. SYMPTOM_TEXT: I got out of bed the morning after the vaccine after having slept/laid down for 12 hours. During that time I was extremely hot but could not break a sweat. My face felt like lava and all my joints were inflamed. There were moments through the night where I'd feel an intense pain in a specific area, it felt like my bone being struck with a hammer. Other times I'd shiver as if my nerves were vibrating. I could feel a throbbing/pulse in my head and ibuprofen seemed to do nothing. My entire body was wrenched in pain, even my eyeballs felt injured. Upon getting out of bed after such a miserable night of supposed rest, I walked up a flight of stairs and had to sit down towards the top because I suddenly felt nauseous. I quickly went back down the stairs hoping I would make it to the bathroom in time. As I lifted up the toilet seat I took a seat on the edge of the bathtub. All I wanted was to wipe off the rim of the bowl with a Clorox towel but even that small task seemed too daunting as I knew my body was starting to turn on me. Throughout my whole being I could feel a wave travel through me as if an electric current had zapped me. Nausea was no longer my concern but rather a dread like something was about to happen but I didn't know what. A pulse hit me which felt similar to when a limb falls asleep and slowly regains circulation however this was all over. The pulse happened twice then my sight started to blur, tunnel vision, as I began to fall backwards into the tub. I never lost consciousness but as I began to feel normal again I instantly felt cold all over. My head felt like I had stuck it in the freezer and chilled me to the bone. As I got out of the tub and snuck a glance in the mirror I was pure white, there was absolutely no color in my face. I went to the living room to rest on the couch and focus on my breathing so as not to have the nausea return. As I did this my whole body felt like it had been asleep, similar to my limb reference earlier, and caused me pain as it regained blood flow. Within 5 minutes I felt normal again but proceeded to have joint pain and fatigue for the rest of the day. On Wednesday I resumed work and my body felt like it had been through an ordeal much like a day of snowboarding and the soreness that comes with it.
OTHER_MEDS: New Chapter Estrotone (Herbal Hormonal Supplement) No meds

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Shingrix Vaccine at 4:50 P.M.; at 4:55 P.M. a headache shot up the back of my head and immediately after a wave of heat went through my body, lightheadedness overcame me and I thought I was going to pass out, tachycardia (114 BPM versus my normal 70), trembling. At 4:59 P.M. I alerted the nurse that I felt "weird." and described my symptoms. It was not an anaphylaxis but, I did feel like I had to take deep breaths in to catch my breath. I felt like I was going to have a heart attack any moment. I asked for an escort in case I passed out and had someone pick me up. My intentions were to go to the hospital parking lot in case my situation got worse. I didn't feel confident that they were equipped at the administration building. They told me that they have an epi pen but, I didn't want to start asking if they knew where the AED machines was. I opted to get a ride to a possible hospital instead. After 30 minutes, I felt like I was "out of the woods." I wasn't 100% but, better. It was extremely scary. I've never had a reaction like this to anything in my life and I'm not allergic to anything.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: On the evening of 11/16, I began feeling itchy all over my body. On 11/17, I woke up in full body hives that swelled further when scratched. Most were on my torso, but I also had them on my legs, feet, arms, and neck. I saw a doctor on 11/19 and was prescribed 1 week of prednisone, and received a referral to get allergy testing related to the Moderna vaccine. The prednisone helped my symptoms, but they did not disappear fully. I have since been taking OTC allergy pills which do alleviate my symptoms, but they persist as of 12/3.  The hives do not appear randomly, but appear when I scratch my skin or at points where my clothing is putting pressure on my skin (ie. bra straps, pants waist, shirt neckline). On April 6, 2021  I was vaccinated with Janssen COVID-19 vaccine one dose lot #042A21A at 3:40PM.      After vaccine I immediately had left sore arm at injection site (lasted one month), dizziness (dissipated after day one), headache, and fatigue.   After one week I had swollen lymph glands under both arm pits for 3 months. Two weeks after injection I had leg pains in both legs.    Hypertension increased and I had to double my hypertension medicine, make it extended release and add a second class of hypertension medicine.  I relieved leg circulation pain by taking a circulatory remedy for 5 days, I was diligent on taking hypertension medication and added Natto kinase in place of aspirin (can?t take aspirin) to reduce any type of blood clotting.  This occurred around the time woman reported blood clotting and drug went on hold. The leg pain was temporary and has dissipated since then.       Since I?ve had the vaccine, I have had  constant fatigue (more than usual) and sporadic headaches have continued over last 6 months.  Some days are worse than others.  I also feel achy with joint and muscle pain.     On 7/28/2021 I tested borderline positive for ANA with no specific indications and then repeated ANA on 8/6/21 testing positive with antibodies indicating two forms of lupus- Systematic Lupus Erythematosus (SLE) and Neuropsychiatric SLE, 4 months after taking vaccine. With our government making this vaccine mandatory and with the CDC stating this vaccine is ?safe? I assumed that I would not have any side effects so I was surprised when I saw my ANA turn positive for lupus.   My ANA antibodies went from borderline positive of 1.4 to definitely positive at 1.8.  I repeated ANA testing on 10/14/21 and my ANA levels remain positive at 1.8.     The risk of taking this vaccine so far has outweighed the benefit from the vaccine.  I have repetitively done the COVID PCR test and I have never been exposed to COVID 19 or any variant in the last 2 years to warrant needing a COVID vaccine. Now, I may have lifelong challenges with side effects from lupus- systematic lupus erythematosus (SLE) and Neuropsychiatric SLE lowering the quality and possibly shortening my life.     SARS COV2 AB IGG bloodwork was repeated on 8/30/2021 and I now have COVID antibodies from the COVID vaccine.  My other concern was micro clotting issue from vaccine as it relates to understanding the headaches, I have experienced in the last 6 months after the vaccine.      A D-dimer test was completed on 8/30 and  10/14 and so far, shows no micro clotting to explain intermittent headaches.   D-dimer will be repeated periodical as well as ANA for lupus over time.    I discussed above with doctor on 8/24/2021 and covered some of the short-term side effects with doctor in previous office consults on May 17, and June 22 to adjust my hypertension medication.   I assumed these symptoms were temporary and would go away so I did not highlight this with my doctor as a possible side effect from vaccine. It was not until my ANA test came back positive and I have other symptoms which are not normal for me (headaches, extreme fatigue, muscle/joint aches)   that I started thinking maybe I am having  medium to long term side effects from the vaccine.     Since my blood pressure was high and doctor had to adjust hypertension medication twice, I established myself with a specialist on July 14 and had (2) heart tests August 5th (ultrasounds EKG and treadmill stress test). I received my ultrasound EKG test on September 29, 2021 and two new issues were found related to my heart which I never had before the vaccine.  I now have mitral and tricuspid regurgitation.  I consulted with  a specialist, on 12/2/2021 as it relates to the  EKG/Ultrasound results done on 8/5/21 and asked if the mitral valve and tricuspid valve regurgitation could be COVID vaccine related .  He said ?nothing comes without a cost? meaning every vaccine comes with risks and benefits.   I initially did not report short term side effects in VAERS because my side effects from vaccine were minor.  Now that I am seeing side effects which may be longer lasting, like lupus and heart valve issues I feel it?s my obligation to report these issues.

3/31/2021, the day after receiving my second Covid vaccination, I was reclining on a couch, relaxing and reading a book. I noticed that the "sound" of my tinnitus was breaking through my focus for reading. I have experienced tinnitus for many years, and it had never before broken my reading focus to this painful extent. Since this initial surprise, the tinnitus "sound" has continued as louder and more sharply penetrating than I had previously experienced - and has increased in intensity. Since April I have had difficulty sleeping (not a tinnitus effect previously), difficulty concentrating in stressful conversations, and difficulty relaxing, as I no longer have quiet available to me. Before March 31 my mild tinnitus did not interfere with the sense of quiet a quiet place afforded. I have also had fantasies of suicide, as suicide would appear to be the only avenue to enjoying quiet again. (Actually, I can enjoy quiet in my dreams - I know I've woken up when I hear the "eeeeekkkkkk" again!) The sound is highly annoying, inherently nerve-racking, and hurts my ears and head! (~8000 hz at ~20-30 db - Think fingernails on a chalkboard).   My internist referred me to an ENT for a hearing test; earliest available appointment 5/14/21. The hearing test showed some loss of hearing and tinnitus. Re the tinnitus, the ENT advised, "It's your brain, not your ears, so I can't do anything for you". In early August my cardiologist prescribed Lisinopril (.25 mg) to address heart function issues (Not treating high blood pressure - my normal blood pressure is 110 over 70, with 16 oz. of coffee in the AM!). Lisinopril reduced my blood pressure to ~ 90 over 60, with coffee). I took this medication 8/11/21�8/27/21 but found that it dramatically increased the feeling of fullness in my ears - and my tinnitus felt like it was intensifying - and I slept very badly during these two weeks (first fantasies of suicide) - so I discontinued taking Lisinopril. While taking Lisinopril I contacted my ENT as the tinnitus seemed to be worsening. My ENT tested my hearing for a second time on 8/24/21 and reported no changes from the 5/14/21 test. The audiologist in the practice recommended full-spectrum CBD to help me fall asleep. I tried this whenever I was having trouble falling asleep, beginning 8/25/21, but eventually found that whenever I thereafter awoke in the middle of the night I suffered a drug-addled, nightmarish struggle to fall back to sleep. (More 3 AM fantasies of suicide).  During this period, 8/25/2021�11/04/2021, I took approximately 45 full spectrum gummies. With increased difficulty achieving a full nights sleep, I tested Night-time Sudafed (1 tablet at ~11 PM each night for 9 nights beginning 10/27/2021) to help me fall asleep and reduce my congestion (And help tinnitus? - I am normally fairly congested and have always had a poor sense of smell!). Night-time Sudafed dropped me off to sleep, but later when I awoke I suffered chills and weird feelings of anxiety, then lethargy the next day. In desperation, on 11/05/2021 I contacted my internist and an endochronologist friend. My friend advised me to "go clean" - no Sudafed, no CBD for 4-5 days - which I did. I have not taken Sudafed or CBD since. During this period I also stopped drinking coffee and alcohol to ensure neither would interfere with my sleep. 11/06/2021 my internist prescribed Lorazepam (.5mg) to help when I cannot fall asleep. I took my first Lorazepam ~11/13/2021 and have taken ~8 since then.  I have also reduced my intake of salt and begun taking a multi-vitamin. I have not been able to identify any correlation between diet, activity... Sound therapy (cricket sounds, forest sounds) has helped offset the effects of the harshness of the tinnitus "sound",  helping me to relax enough to fall asleep. Since August I have spent at least $1,000 on various headphones, speakers, and apps to deliver soothing sounds to my brain! In early November I also identified several ENT's who advertise as addressing tinnitus in their practice. I have an appointment 12/14/2021 with one such ENT, who I hope will offer some medical insight and possible measures to pursue to lessen the "noise". In addition, I speak with a psychiatrist every 3�4 weeks, at a cost to me of $150 per session (no insurance involved). Since April, coping with tinnitus has become a dominant theme of our discussions.

HISTORY: Tinnitus (mild, since 1980's); Sensorineural hearing loss in both ears (minor loss first noted ~2003); Sarcoidosis / mediastinal and hilar lymphadenopathy (diagnosed 2018), mild, untreated (no effect on heart or eyes); Functional heart murmur (since childhood);  Hypercholesteremia (since 1980's), treated with various statins for over 15 years until 2018, 2018 Calcium test score = ZERO, (10/26/2021, untreated, fasting Total|HDL|Tri|LDL = 330|65|75|247 mg/DL); Statin myopathy (diagnosed 2014); Left-bundle-branch-block (since ~2006); Non-ischemic cardiomyopathy (diagnosed 2019); Impaired fasting glucose (fluctuating since 2015); Osteopenia (diagnosed 2015); Herniated intervertebral disc (since 2003); Degeneration of lumbar intervertebral disc (2014); Scoliosis of lumbar spine (2019);  Hip pain, left (1994); Osteoarthritis of left hip (2014); Dysthymia (1986 to present); Menopause (2009)

SYMPTOM_TEXT: 53 yo M with multiple allergies and known "anaphylactic" reaction to the Covid19 vaccine was in clinic for his third dose COVID vaccine (Moderna) on 11/9/21 at 1033.  Per chart records, reaction following 2nd injection included nausea/vomiting, tachycardia, and chest pressure which started 15 seconds after getting the vaccine.  Symptoms required admission to the hospital for 2 days. Other symptoms included occasional chills, mild pruritic persistent rash.  Per patient, his MDs recommended he should get the 3rd dose.   Unknown if he was premedicated.   Approx 10 minutes after receiving the 3rd vaccine 0.5ml dose (lot # 032F21A) in the right deltoid, he developed hives that included intense generalized pruritis and erythematous patchy rash on his arms.  The patient was treated 25mg IM diphenhydramine with no improvement after 10 minutes.  Symptoms worsening and pruritis spreading to lower legs and plantar surfaces.  Additional 25mg IM diphenhydramine was given which totaled of 75 mg IM Benadryl. Patient was monitored for about 2 hours prior to being discharged. Transport called and taken to meet his wife at the front lobby.  At 1115, pruritis had subsided.  At 1140, the pruritis had returned.  Patient was given another 25 mg of IM diphenhydramine.  At 1215, pruritis had again resolved.  Patient feels drowsy, but is otherwise symptom free.  Remained symptom free and was discharged with wife to be driven home.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I was given the 3rd dose of the Moderna, the booster shot, on October 29, 2021. I started to feel unwell on October 30, 2021. At first, I felt the symptoms I was told I was going to feel such as the fever, body aches, and chills. Later that same day, around 4:30 p.m., I started to experience a sharp pain at the beginning of my spine. I felt extremely dizzy along with a headache. Throughout the night, I felt the pain get worse and I took Tylenol in order to relieve the pain. I took Tylenol and it helped put the pain at ease, although the pain never seemed to have went away.  Starting on November 28, 2021, the pain came back even worse than before. I am unable to move nor walk due to this pain. My spine and back appear to be inflamed. I feel extremely dizzy and my legs feel very weak. I felt an unbearable amount of pain so I went to the Emergency Department on November 30, 2021. There, the doctor told me I have acute bilateral low back pain without running any tests or listening to my other symptoms.  I was sent home the same day with 4 medications: Naproxen (Naprosyn 500 mg oral tablet), Diazepam (Valium 5 mg oral tablet), Hydromorphone (Dilaudid 4 mg oral tablet), Methylprednisolone (Medrol dosepak 4mg oral tablet). I was still unable to  move or walk, my legs still felt extremely weak, and I was still in immense pain. I went to Hospital on December 1, 2021. There, I was given Lidocaine and Pantoprazole. I was discharged at 4:38 p.m. on December 2, 2021 and was prescribed 2 medications: Ibuprofen and Lidocaine. I was told to return  if the pain becomes worse or if other symptoms appear. I am currently at home taking the prescribed medication unable to move. I can barely make it out of bed. I have not been able to work since November 29th, 2021. It is December 3rd, 2021 and the pain remains and I am waiting for this medication to help.

Started the evening of 11/18 ? my left back thigh and inner right thigh were itchy.  I could feel a bunch of small bumps.  At 1:30am I woke up with intense itchiness.  I took a picture to see the bumps.  They were smallish welts/hives that looked similar to the reaction I have to mosquito bites.  I put on over the counter hydrocortisone, which helped calm the itching.  Then, I started to notice that I was getting itchy other places ? my back, side, stomach.  I continued to put hydrocortisone to ease the itchiness.  By 8am on Friday the 19th, I had red patches in various places ? legs, stomach, back, upper arms.  I took a Claritin and continued to use hydrocortisone to ease the itching throughout the day.   The hives would come and go throughout the day. 11/20 ? woke up with red itchy patches in armpit and surrounding area, back, thighs/groin/leg crease area.  I took Benadryl and used hydrocortisone throughout the day.  The areas continued to stay red, would itch and hives/welts would come and go.  I went to Urgent Care that evening.  While I mentioned to the medical assistant that I think it could have been caused by my booster, I don?t think I relayed that information to the NP who treated me.  I received a shot of mtheylprednisolone 125mg and famotidine 40mg at urgent care and a prescription for hydroxyzine 25mg.  Shortly after the shot in the butt, my lower back burst into hives.  The NP told me if it didn?t get better soon that I need to go to the ER.  The hives eventually went away within the hour.  Interestingly, when I took the bandaid off from shot, my skin was bright red where the bandaid adhered to my body.  No itching or hives, just bright red.  I then started to notice that my skin would turn red with the smallest ?trauma? ? scratching, holding a bag on my arm, seams from clothes.  Sometimes it would cause hives to appear and itch.   11/21 ? I woke up with all of the red patches gone, no itching, no hives.  The red patches that I had in my leg crease and lower back had turned brown (not my normal skin color).  By 11/22, the brown color had disappeared.  I continued to take the hydroxyzine. 11/22 ? most of the day was free of any redness, hives and itching.  By the evening, I had started to notice red areas on my arm, back, and stomach.  But I don?t recall it being too itchy. 11/23 ? Woke up with a red itching and hurting patch in my armpit and surrounding area.  I took Benadryl (not hydroxyzine because I had to work and feared the drowsiness) and used hydrocortisone.  That evening, I used my son?s Aveeno Baby eczema balm on my armpits to try and prevent another flare. 11/24 ? woke up with large red patches/flares on my thighs and sides, hips, back.  I used Eucrin baby eczema cream to help and continued with Benadryl. I would take Benadryl during the day and hydroxyxzine in the evening/bed.   11/25 ? random and various areas continued to flare and itched. Appearance of red spots on knees and lower legs on 11/17. Slight progression of spots on calves. Seemed like it was an allergic reaction to a newly purchased body wash. Discontinued use of body wash. On 11/26, I received intravenous toradol and reglan with oral meclizine and Benadryl to address a severe headache and nausea  that started on 11/24 and would not subside. The red spots increased on 11/28 to  my trunk, thighs, and elbows. The dermatologist did a biopsy and the results were returned today, 12/3. The spots have spread to my ankles and feet as well. I have been diagnosed with leukocytoclastic vasculitis. I started a regiment of prednisone today which will be  scheduled to end in 5 weeks. Overall symptoms include hard red spots which turn  reddish purple with long bouts of sitting or standing. My legs, ankles, and feet have swelling and throb. The swelling subsides significantly after sleeping for the night.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient is a 78-year-old female who presented to the emergency department on 11/18/21 with complaint of fever, diffuse myalgias and malaise.  She is a poor historian.  States onset of symptoms was yesterday at some point.  States he had some nasal congestion and felt some chills and generally felt poorly.  She is fully vaccinated for COVID with the Moderna vaccine completed about 6 months ago.  Is uncertain where she would have exposed.  In the emergency department she was noted to have fever of just under 103�.  She has been doing some extra work of breathing with borderline hypoxia.  She denies that she has been wheezing.  States she has been coughing but no purulent sputum.  No nausea or vomiting.  Blood pressure has been stable.  Secondary to the borderline respiratory status and her fever she is being admitted to the hospital.Chest x-ray was positive for right lower lung atelectasis and also  had COVID test that was positive.  Cardiac BNP, troponin, blood cultures are  all negative.  The patient was admitted in the hospital and also tried IV ,  then ceftriaxone and azithromycin, and patient tolerated fairly well, and  also had infection markers.  Ferritin was 124 and cardiac BNP was negative.   Lactic acid was only 1.37.  Troponin was negative.  White blood count and  hemoglobin were normal.  Liver function tests were normal and patient was able  to walk fairly well in the room with no hypoxia and down to 89 for a few  seconds and then came back up, and she is comfortable going home.  Patient was  advised to be discharged on p.o. dexamethasone for a few more days and p.o.  Levaquin every other day for 5 more doses, and follow up as an outpatient. Discharged on 11/20/21

Presented to ER on 11/27/21 and admitted. This is an elderly 82-year-old Caucasian gentleman with history of dementia,  prior history of CVA as well as CKD stage 4, who was brought to the local  emergency room at Hospital with a fever of 101.6,  complaining of generalized malaise.  Also he was found to be COVID positive  and chest x-ray was showing questionable left lower lobe pneumonia.  Also his  lactic acid was slightly high at 2.8; repeat one being 2.1.  The patient does  have a history of BPH.  They placed a Foley catheter in him and the patient  was supposed to go to Clinic, but as per the family's request, they  called another location.  When I spoke to the ER doctor, the patient had not gotten any  treatment, no Decadron, no remdesivir, and since his onset of symptoms is  relatively new and he is hypoxemic requiring 3 L of oxygen, he was deemed to  be a candidate for both remdesivir and Decadron, which was then requested to  be started over there.  When I saw the patient, he is pleasantly confused.  He  is oriented times 2, knows his name, knows that he is at this hospital.  His  vital signs are relatively stable.  He is saturating well on 3 L nasal  cannula.  He will be admitted as an inpatient to our COVID-19 floor. Patient was weaned of oxygen, was afebrile. SYMPTOM_TEXT: Briefly this is a 5 yo F with hx of neonatal stroke with L sided weakness and epilepsy presenting with breakthrough seizure. Pt had COVID-19 vaccine 2 days ago. Visiting. No fevers, URI sx. Typical seizure starts with vomiting, hand jerking/shaking, and L eye deviation. Last breakthrough seizure in Feb 2021. Sibling with runny nose. 5 yo F with epilepsy and breakthrough seizure. No symptoms of illness. Unclear if COVID vaccination was trigger for breakthrough seizure. Upon arrival, pt was post-ictal with intermittent L eye deviation and now with hand jerking which was concerning for ongoing seizure activity. Pt was given intranasal midazolam with improvement, but seizure activity returned prompting IV ativan and IV keppra load. Seizure activity stopped and pt became responsive to voice but post-ictal. 2nd IV access obtained. Labs sent with normal glucose, reassuring CBC and electrolytes. Depakote level is in therapeutic range. Pt given home dose of depakote IV (missed AM dose). Neuro at the bedside throughout resuscitation.    COVID neg.     Care transitioned to the inpatient  Neurology attending. Pt was stable at the time of admission. MRI Brain 11/12/21: IMPRESSION: Images were significantly degraded by motion artifact. 1.No evidence of acute intracranial abnormality within limitation of motion artifact. 2.Posterior frontal porencephalic cyst with associated paucity of posterior frontal and right parietal periventricular white matter. On the morning of discharge, smile was symmetric, but she was noted to be ataxic, although much less than the day prior, so we drew a peak VPA level which was 150 (peak), with otherwise normal LFTs, normal platelets and no other signs of VPA toxicity. Thus, it was felt that the ataxia is likely secondary to medication effects in the last 24-48hrs with relatively high depakote level, Midaz 0.5mg/kg total, IV Ativan, and addition of Levetiracetam. Higher level of depakote was attributed to increased bioavailability of IV medication.  We observed her through the afternoon and felt that she was stable for discharge with close Neurology follow-up with Dr. calling on Tuesday 11/16/21. We will request Neurology follow up in clinic prior to  at the end of the month.  Family is considering whether they will get her the 2nd dose of COVID vaccine.  Risks and benefits discussed.  Discussed not flying back within 2 days of dose as much harder to manage if she were to have a prolonged seizure in flight.
OTHER_MEDS: Clonazepam 0.125 mg PO BID PRN seizure, levetiracetam 400 mg PO BID, diastat 10 mg PR PRN seizure, valproic acid 475 mg PO BID,

In summary, patient is a 19-year-old with new onset diabetes.  She has hyperglycemia without acidosis.  She has received her first dose of subcu insulin.  She understands her diagnosis.  She is eager to be able to go home but understands the need to be admitted for education.  In discussions with the family, family is concerned that diabetes is from her Pfizer Covid vaccine which she received in August.  I have discussed this with pharmacist.  That time.  Is quite long to be a side effect.  Additionally endocrinopathies have not been previously described.  The family is reassured that we are taking that concern seriously.  They also understand that this is unlikely to be related to the vaccine.  As per attending admission policy, endocrine fellow spoke to accepting attending.  Patient transferred to inpatient unit for education and diabetes management.  Admission HPI: Patient is a healthy 19F with PMH of vasovagal syncope, eczema and allergic rhinitis who presented to the ED with 4 weeks of polydipsia and polyuria.     Patient is a student and began noticing that she had a dry mouth and was excessively thirsty a few weeks ago. She jokingly said she had diabetes but did not think much of it. She also noticed she was urinating more frequently, waking up in the middle of the night to drink and void. She has also had a 10lb weight loss over the last few months. Denies any abdominal pain or nausea/vomiting or other preceding infection or illness during this period.      She is home this weekend visiting her parents, and noticed she was drinking gallons of water, so she wanted to have this evaluated, so she went to her pediatrician where she had an elevated blood sugar level and was referred to  ED for further evaluation.     In the ED, she was HDS, mildly tachycardic with a well-appearing with an exam notable for non-tender abdomen. Labs were notable for glucose 319, BOHB 4.45, pH 7.35/41.9, bicarb 20, AG 17, and HbA1c 12.4%. Reassuringly, her kidney function was normal. She was diagnosed with new-onset diabetes, but was reassuringly not in DKA. Endocrine was consulted and she was initiated on a subcutaneous insulin regimen and admitted for further management.   Confidential social history:   - Sexually active, uses protection and is on birth control. Has her period currently.  - Uses alcohol and tobacco socially, no recreational drug use  - Feels safe at home and school  Hospital Course: Patient was admitted to the endocrine team with diabetes mellitus.   The patient presented with several weeks of polyuria, polydipsia, and weight loss. The blood glucose level on arrival to the ED was 319 mg/dL.  Initial laboratory evaluation included bicarbonate 20 mEq/, anion gap 17 mEq/L, venous pH 7.35, and ketonuria. Hemoglobin A1c was 12.4%.  This presentation was diagnostic of diabetes mellitus.   Given a history of elevated BMI, a gradual onset of symptoms, a diagnosis of type 2 diabetes was considered most likely. Confirmatory antibody testing is pending.   Patient was initiated on a basal-bolus insulin regimen with Lantus and Humalog. The insulin regimen was adjusted to achieve adequate glycemic control prior to discharge. Final insulin regimen is in the patient instruction section of the discharge summary.   Family education was provided by diabetic nurse educators and nutritionists regarding basic concepts and skills for diabetes management.  At the time of discharge, parent(s)/primary caregiver(s) demonstrated understanding of these concepts and adequate technical skills for safe diabetes management until the follow-up visit. Following discharge, patient and family will follow up with Endocrinology team at Hospital.
OTHER_MEDS: ethinyl estradiol-norgestimate 35 mcg - 0.25 mg 1 tab PO daily
CUR_ILL: vasovagal syncope, 4 week hx of rhinitis

SYMPTOM_TEXT: With the second dose the onset of symptoms was more rapid and much more severe. I came home from work at 9 p.m. feeling awful as if I had come down with the flu. I immediately went to bed. I experienced uncontrollable shaking, sweating, chills, and a fever. I want to especially state for posterity that I felt like whatever was injected in me was changing my body section by section at a cellular level. I have never gone through any type of experience like that in my life.  This time I felt inflammation in my heart and in my brain. Perhaps it was because I was forced to take this series of injections, but I feel there was something in the second shot that a pharmaceutical engineer put together to fundamentally change my body. I chose to rest for the next 3 days. I felt some aches and pains as I did with the first shot after the symptoms  I just described above  over the next 24 hours.  I can say that by Tuesday, 11/29/21, I was able to resume work and by the end of the week I felt relatively normal.  I really feel I must share with the world the effects the Pfizer shot had on my body so they know that it's can have some significant side effects and in my mind permanent damage to the body.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I am 37 years old, 5' 3", 115 lbs.    An hour after receiving the first dose, I experienced increased rapid heart rate while maintaining a resting position. This lasted for 2 hours. In early April, I noticed that the superficial veins in my arms had become quite inflamed. Inflamed veins such as these are more typical of those of a bodybuilder, I do not do strenuous lifting at all.  At first, they would appear when it was warm out (about 70 degrees F). Yet as the weeks progressed, the inflammation occurred more frequently, regardless of warm temperatures.   As of this day, Dec. 04, 2021, there is more pooling of blood within the veins of my arms.  They are almost always inflamed. I experience itching and a sensation that something is crawling underneath my skin. The heart palpatations no longer occur. I do not have inflamed veins in any other part of my body.

On an unknown date, the patient went on a vegan diet and was in remission for 11 years. The patient only had couple of minor flares during those 11 years and only thing she took was ibuprofen only when she had a flare. The patient stated that her left hand looks as if someone put air in it, you could not see the knuckles, it was just giant and swollen and she could not move it and it was painful and was feeling like she need to go back on her Enbrel because this had been persistent for the last six months since she got the covid shot. Causality Assessment: Rheumatoid arthritis flare up Per Company (Amgen) = No; Sender's Comments: The event rheumatoid arthritis flare up is considered more likely to be part of the natural clinical course of the underlying disease but unrelated to etanercept or BNT162B2.

he began having symptoms of acute pericarditis a month and a half after the 2nd dose/diagnosed with pericarditis; lightheaded and dizziness; Covid symptoms for 1 day after the 2nd dose; This spontaneous case was reported by a consumer and describes the occurrence of PERICARDITIS (he began having symptoms of acute pericarditis a month and a half after the 2nd dose/diagnosed with pericarditis) in a 69-year-old male patient who received mRNA-1273 (Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine) (batch no. 016B21A) for COVID-19 vaccination. The occurrence of additional non-serious events is detailed below.     The patient's past medical history included COVID-19 (Symptoms began, beginning of December then again on 16 or 17 Dec 2020. COVID-19 test was performed on 30-Dec-2020 which got positive.) in December 2020.    On 25-Mar-2021, the patient received second dose of mRNA-1273 (Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine) (unknown route) 1 dosage form. In March 2021, the patient experienced SUSPECTED COVID-19 (Covid symptoms for 1 day after the 2nd dose). On 25-Mar-2021, the patient experienced DIZZINESS (lightheaded and dizziness). On 05-Jun-2021, the patient experienced PERICARDITIS (he began having symptoms of acute pericarditis a month and a half after the 2nd dose/diagnosed with pericarditis) (seriousness criterion medically significant). The patient was treated with COLCHICINE for Pericarditis, at a dose of 1 dosage form. At the time of the report, PERICARDITIS (he began having symptoms of acute pericarditis a month and a half after the 2nd dose/diagnosed with pericarditis) was resolving, DIZZINESS (lightheaded and dizziness) outcome was unknown and SUSPECTED COVID-19 (Covid symptoms for 1 day after the 2nd dose) had resolved.            No concomitant medication information provided.   Patient received booster dose (lot # 065F21A) on 23-Nov-2021 of the Moderna Covid-19 Vaccine. He had Covid symptoms for one day after the second dose. Right away after the second dose he felt lightheaded and dizzy. He began symptoms of acute pericarditis a month and a half after the second dose and was diagnosed with pericarditis on 05-Jun-2021. He had heart attack symptoms such as chest pain on his left side radiating to chest bone, his back, and left shoulder. He went to the ER 4 times with false symptoms of a heart attack. He would wake up with a sharp pain on his left side before doing anything that would last a short time then go away. But then he would be able to climb stairs with no trouble at all, which was confusing. It started as strong, dull pain, then he was ok for about 2 weeks, then it changed to sharp pain and episodes of fatigue that lasted from 30 seconds to 1 minute and a half. He also said the second wave of pain episodes would happen 2 to 3 times a day and last 20 seconds to a minute and a half. Also when laying down he couldn't breathe. He states that the symptoms are continuing but much less frequent and much less intense. Patient would continue to see a cardiologist. On an unknown date EKG, blood work, echograms, and a CT scan done because of suspected blood clot, unknown results.  Company Comment: This spontaneous case concerns a 69-year-old male patient with no details on relevant medical history, who experienced the expected serious (medically significant) event of Pericarditis and the non serious event of Suspected COVID-19 (AESI) after mRNA- 1273 Moderna vaccine. The onset of Pericarditis occurred 1 month and a half after the second dose and the diagnosis was confirmed approximately 2 months and 6 days after the second dose. Clinical manifestations included Chest pain, Fatigue and Dyspnoea. Electrocardiogram, laboratory, echocardiogram and CT scan were performed, but results are not available. Outpatient treatment with colchicine was given. At the time of the report, the symptoms were resolving. The rechallenge is not applicable, since the events were reported exclusively after the second dose. The benefit-risk relationship of mRNA- 1273 vaccine is not affected by this report. Therapeutic measures were taken as a result of drug-induced liver injury. Clinical course and discussion: A 61-year-old female with a known history of irritable bowel disease and cholecystectomy presented to the emergency department with generalized weakness, body aches, dry heaving, and a low-grade temperature of 99.9 Fahrenheit. The patient received a second dose of the Pfizer COVID-19 vaccine nine days before the start of symptoms. She was noted to have conjunctival icterus, mild generalized abdominal tenderness without guarding, or rigidity on physical examination. On admission, the patient's vitals were stable except for tachycardia with a heart rate between 90 and 110 beats/min. Laboratory analysis was remarkable for elevated alkaline phosphatase (ALP) of 207 U/L, total bilirubin of 6.2 mg/dL, direct bilirubin of 3.9 mg/dL, white blood cell (WBC) count of 17.2 x 10^9 /L, and mildly elevated aspartate transaminase of 37 U/L (Table 1 "Liver function tests trend" and Figure 1 "Graphs showing liver function test trends"). Abdominal ultrasound showed increased echogenicity within the liver compatible with fatty infiltrates, and common duct diameter was measured to be 6 mm. At the same time, CT of the abdomen with contrast showed no acute abnormalities. The patient was admitted to the hospital and started on empiric antibiotics for presumed cholangitis. Gastroenterology consultation was obtained. Magnetic resonance cholangiopancreatography without contrast showed no filling defect within the biliary duct, status post cholecystectomy, bile duct diameter within a normal range, and unremarkable liver. The patient remained afebrile, WBC trended down, and abdominal pain improved over the course of the hospital stay. Given these findings, infectious disease specialist recommended discontinuing antibiotics. Antibodies to liver/kidney microsomal type 1, smooth muscle, anti-mitochondrial, alpha-1 antitrypsin came back negative, and, additionally, ceruloplasmin, antinuclear antibody, alpha fetoprotein, and viral serologies for hepatitis A, B, and C came back negative (Table 2 "Immunologic and infectious work-up for liver disease"). Liver biopsy showed minimal pallor suggesting slight edema along with scattered inflammatory cells consisting of small lymphocytes, scattered polymorphonuclear leukocytes, and few eosinophils, no evidence of florid duct lesion on interface hepatitis, and no evidence of fibrosis on trichrome and reticulin stain. Given that all work-up for infection, autoimmune diseases, and any obstruction came back negative, the patient's clinical picture and laboratory findings were attributed as a liver injury due to the COVID-19 vaccine. Her liver function levels continued to trend down, and she was discharged from the hospital after a week of hospitalization. On the patient's follow-up with a gastroenterologist, abdominal pain was resolved, and her liver function test values normalized (Table 1 and Figure 1). In this case, the review of medications and history did not reveal any other reason for hepatotoxicity. She also denied the use of any over-the-counter medications or supplements. Although it is rare with vaccination, the COVID-19 vaccine is likely the cause of hepatotoxicity in our patient based on a diagnosis of exclusion. In this case, the patient had a cholestatic pattern with elevated ALP and bilirubin with mild elevation in the transaminases. This patient has underlying fatty liver disease. It is unclear if that was a likely risk factor for hepatotoxicity in this case. Hepatotoxicity can occur with vaccines, even though it is more common with prescription and nonprescription drugs. So, the clinician should be watchful in patients showing clinical signs and symptoms after a vaccine. In summary, we presented a case of liver injury after the COVID-19 vaccine. We attributed the cause of liver injury to the COVID-19 vaccine, given no other cause in our patient after extensive work-up. There are reports of drug-induced liver injury and abnormal liver function analysis from the spontaneous reports from patients who received Pfizer/BioNTech BNT162b2 mRNA COVID-19 vaccine. The purpose of this manuscript is to raise awareness of potential side effects; it should not alter the recommendation of healthcare providers regarding vaccinations.   No follow-up attempts are possible; information about lot/batch number cannot be obtained. No further information is expected.; Sender's Comments: Based on the information provided a contributory role of BNT162B2 to the event liver injury cannot be fully excluded. Underlying fatty liver may also be contributory. The impact of this report on the benefit/risk profile of the Pfizer product is evaluated as part of Pfizer procedures for safety evaluation, including the review and analysis of aggregate data for adverse events. Any safety concern identified as part of this review, as well as any appropriate action in response, will be promptly notified to regulatory authorities, Ethics Committees, and Investigators, as appropriate.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: 10/10 headache; Hypotensive; tachycardic; nausea and vomiting; nausea and vomiting; body shakes; shivers; hypertension; This is a spontaneous report from a contactable registered nurse. A 16 year-old female patient received meningococcal group b rlp2086 (TRUMENBA), administered in deltoid left, administration date 17Nov2021 12:09 (Lot number: ER2622, NDC number: 0005-0100-10, Expiration Date: Jan2024) at the age of 16 years as dose number unknown, 0.5 ml, single for immunisation; influenza vaccine (FLUZONE), intramuscular, administered in deltoid right, administration date 17Nov2021 (Lot number: UT7411KA, Expiration Date: 30Jun2022) as 0.5 ml, single; meningococcal vaccine a/c/y/w conj (dip tox) (MENACTRA), intramuscular, administered in deltoid right, administration date 17Nov2021 (Lot number: U7207AB, Expiration Date: 08Feb2023) as 0.5 ml, single. Relevant medical history included: "Asthma" (unspecified if ongoing). There were no concomitant medications. No prior vaccination within 4 weeks. No AE following prior vaccination.  The following information was reported: HEADACHE (medically significant) with onset 17Nov2021, outcome "recovered" (Nov2021), described as "10/10 headache"; HYPOTENSION (medically significant) with onset 17Nov2021, outcome "recovered" (Nov2021), described as "Hypotensive"; TACHYCARDIA (medically significant) with onset 17Nov2021, outcome "recovered" (Nov2021), described as "tachycardic"; VOMITING (medically significant), NAUSEA (medically significant) all with onset 17Nov2021, outcome "recovered" (Nov2021) and all described as "nausea and vomiting"; TREMOR (non-serious) with onset 17Nov2021, outcome "recovered" (Nov2021), described as "body shakes"; CHILLS (non-serious) with onset 17Nov2021, outcome "recovered" (Nov2021), described as "shivers"; HYPERTENSION (non-serious) with onset 17Nov2021, outcome "recovered" (Nov2021), described as "hypertension". Within an hour of receiving the vaccines, the patient had a 10 out of 10 headache, body shakes, shivers, nausea. Around 1:30PM, the patients' mom was calling about this and then the patient was taken to the ER. The patient was hypotensive, tachycardic and had nausea and vomiting, also had hypertension. T3 thyroid hormone was a little high; perhaps he lifted something and injured his rotator cuff; Pain shooting towards his hand (left); Cannot lift his left arm above the level of his eyes or so, in other works he cannot lift his left arm up over his head; Initial information received on 16-Nov-2021 regarding an unsolicited valid non-serious case from a consumer/non-health care professional via Agency (under reference number 00859892).  This case involves a 73 years old male patient whose T3 thyroid hormone was a little high (tri-iodothyronine increased), had pain shooting towards his hand (left) (pain), cannot lift his left arm above the level of his eyes or so, in other works he cannot lift his left arm up over his head (injected limb mobility decreased)perhaps he lifted something and injured his rotator cuff (rotator cuff syndrome), after receiving INFLUENZA QUADRIVAL A-B HIGH DOSE HV VACCINE [FLUZONE HIGH-DOSE QUADRIVALENT].  The patient's past medical treatment(s), vaccination(s) and family history were not provided.  At the time of the event, the patient has medical condition of high blood pressure and has concomitant HYDROCHLOROTHIAZIDE (12.5 mg, other dosing details not reported) for it.  Patient received no other concomitant vaccines.  On 05-Oct-2021, the patient received a 0.7 ml dose of suspect INFLUENZA QUADRIVAL A-B HIGH DOSE HV VACCINE (injection, total, lot number and expiration date not reported) via an unknown route in the left deltoid for prophylactic vaccination.  On 05-Oct-2021, the patient developed a non-serious pain shooting towards his hand (left) (pain)and cannot lift his left arm above the level of his eyes or so, in other works he cannot lift his left arm up over his head (injected limb mobility decreased), on the same day following the administration of INFLUENZA QUADRIVAL A-B HIGH DOSE HV VACCINE.  On an unknown date, the patient perhaps lifted something and injured his rotator cuff (rotator cuff syndrome) (unknown latency) following the administration of INFLUENZA QUADRIVAL A-B HIGH DOSE HV VACCINE.  On an unknown date, the patient developed a non-serious T3 thyroid hormone was a little high (tri-iodothyronine increased) (unknown latency) following the administration of INFLUENZA QUADRIVAL A-B HIGH DOSE HV VACCINE.  It was reported "73 years old male, received FLUZONE HIGH DOSE on 05OCT2021, is experiencing pain he describes as shooting towards his hand (left) and can not lift arm; caller states he has NOT seen his primary care physician  (PCP) regarding the matter; caller was transferred from SANOFI customer service; Upon transfer, patient asked about the above symptoms, how long it might last and is there anything he can do for it. Patient received a Fluzone High-Dose Quadrivalent vaccine on 05 Oct 2021 in the left deltoid, and he was 72 at that time. Patient received no concomitant vaccines. Patient stated that the "claim reference number" for his Fluzone High-Dose injection was 79770074, and the prescription number is 0791900-14206, and the National Drug Code  (NDC) number is 49281-0121-65. Since that time, the patient has been experiencing the symptoms described above. Patient stated that he cannot lift his left arm above the level of his eyes or so, in other works he cannot lift his left arm up over his head. Patient stated he is not sure what is going on, perhaps he lifted something and injured his rotator cuff, he just does not know. Patient said he has had complete blood work done, and everything is normal, except that his T3 thyroid hormone is a little high. Patient stated that the only medication he takes is 12.5 mg of hydrochlorothiazide for high blood pressure. Patient stated that later today (16 Nov 2021) he is going to receive a booster injection of the Moderna Covid-19 vaccine in his right arm."  Other relevant laboratory test were not reported.  It was not reported if the any corrective treatment was given or not.  At the time of reporting, the patient did not recover from any of the reported events.
