On 03/09/2021, after having my second Covid vaccine, I had chills and was very fatigued but that went away by 2:30 PM. The next day, 03/10/2021, I awoke after sleeping very deep and when I went to walk, I PASSED OUT, hit my head and wrenched my neck. I put on an watch later that morning and within a few hours it alerted me that I was in Atrial Fibrillation. The AFIB came on with a vengeance. My heart rate was high and I headed to the ER about 6:00 PM. I was diagnosed with AFIB and was admitted to the hospital and put on medication. I saw my own cardiologist for a few months. The AFIB continued to get worse during the spring and I went to an electrophysiologist and it was suggested I get an ablation but it  but it couldn't be scheduled for three months due to the EP's full schedule. During the summer I had events where I would feel like I was going to pass out unless I sat down.  If effected my work because I would have episodes where I just had to sit all day due to how I would feel. I had two (summer & fall 2020) episodes prior to my 2nd Covid shot, but nothing was really ever diagnosed except one time the monitor recorded an SVT - Paroxysmal Supraventricular Tachycardia. The second Covid shot really changed my life and not for the better. I finally had my heart ablation on 11/4/2021. Now I wait, in the blanking period, to see if it was successful or not. I'm very concerned about getting the booster shot -- fearful it will make me have another heart situation.
LAB_DATA: 3/10/2021 - Heart monitor 3/11/2021 - echocardiogram Various EKG's, echocardiograms & three week monitor on various dates
OTHER_MEDS: Synthroid, minocycline, lisinopril, baby aspirin, vitamin D, p, Omega 3, probiotic
HISTORY: hypothryoidism, non-specific autoimmune disease, dupuytren's disease

SYMPTOM_TEXT: 12 year-old patient received their first dose of the Pfizer Adult vaccine on November 5, 2021.  Patient was inadvertently given the Pfizer Pediatric 5-11 dose (.2ml) on November 26, 2021, as their second dose.  The parent was informed of the administration error as soon as it was detected.  The patient had no adverse reaction.   Per the CDC guidance on COVID-19 Vaccine Administration Errors, if a person aged 12 -17 yrs is given the 5-11 years formulation as the second dose, the patient is considered fully vaccinated and no additional vaccine should be administered to the patient. In an effort to implement best practices and avoid any vaccine administration error in the future, our practice has taken additional steps to include the following: each Pfizer formulation is stored in distinct containers and in different areas of the refrigerator.  Brightly colored, easily recognizable Pediatric labels are affixed to the syringes containing the pediatric formulation to distinguish them from the Pfizer vaccine for persons 12 years and older.  Providers and support staff are also reminded to always verify the age of the patient and the appropriate vaccine to administer.

I only took one pill the day I got it and the next day and I did not take it after that. It did help with the joint pain. And tizanidine, I only took one night. The underlying fatigue, joint pain and muscle pain I just dealt with it until 11/23/2021 when the hives hit. I thought it was going to go away, full body hives. By Thursday night, I had a telehealth appointment. They prescribed prednisone, Zyrtec and on Friday. I had another telehealth appointment with my doctor. To continue the prednisone, continue the Zyrtec, and add Pepcid and get an allergy appointment. I had an allergy appointment on 12/06/2021. They told me to get off all the antihistamines prior to taking the allergy test. Now I am on Singulair, Allegra Zyrtec and Pepcid. When I don't have to take medication, then I will call that recovered from my adverse events. Diagnosis: Spontaneous idiopathic urticaria.

Patient received a dose of Pfizer COVID-19Vaccine  Peds formulation (5-11yr) that may have been reconstituted with a single use vial of 0.9%NS that was entered into multiple times to reconstitute other vials of Pfizer vaccine. Staff did not realize the 10mL vial  was for single use only (to take out 1.3mL then discard). Each time the vial was used it was swabbed with alcohol and a new syringe was used to enter the vial then to add the diluent to the Pfizer vaccine for reconstitution. The 10mL ,  0.9%NS vial was disposed of at the end of each day. The patient did not experience any adverse reaction. At the recommendation of Pfizer, due to lack of stability data, it was advised to revaccinate the patient.

Client received vaccine at 10:42am and was sitting in clinic to be observed for 15 minutes. Client asked nurse to come over because he was feeling lightheaded and was sweaty. RN noticed client was very pale and diaphoretic. Client began to pass out and RN assisted him to the floor. Clients legs were elevated on a chair, cold washcloth placed on his head, and pillow placed under his head. Client opened his eyes about to 10-15 seconds later. Clients heart rate was 62 and blood pressure 80/52 . Offered client some juice and crackers and had him to continue to lay down until he started feeling better.  After 15 minutes rechecked blood pressure 120/80 assisted client to sitting position then gradually helped him to stand and helped him sit in chair. Client ate two peanut butter crackers and had some juice, Client was observed for another 15 minutes. stated he was feeling better and was ready to go home. Nurse walked him to the door. Client called when he made it home and stated he was feeling better and was going to eat some lunch.  Another RN called Client on 12/7/2021 at 9:30am to check on him. Client stated he had some muscle aches, soreness and chills but he had that with his two first COVID shots. Client s tated he made an appointment with his doctoor on 12/13/2021 to follow up.

52 year old female who upon receiving her first dose of Pfizer vaccine, had a severe adverse reaction.    Before receiving the vaccination, all screening questions were reviewed with the client, when asked about any allergies, per client she mentioned that she did have some allergies to several medications (Percocet) and certain foods, which she avoided. When asked about severity, she said that she had itchiness, hives, and some swelling, but never required the use of an epinephrine pen. The client stated that she was anxious but otherwise in good health and that the only medications she was currently taking were steroids.    The client received the vaccine at 7:10 PM, because of her history of allergic reactions, she was asked to wait 30 minutes in the observation area. As the client was about to leave, she began to feel unwell, and ?felt dizzy? with ?the worse headache of her life?. She was moved from the observation area to a chair in the lobby. A set of vitals were taken by RN.    7:50 PM VS HR 70s, oxygen sat 99%, BP 180/119   At this time the client is AO and complaining of numbness in her lips and that her throat felt a little itchy. Upon exam, her lips appeared swollen. Throat and lungs were clear. 25 mg of Benadryl (lot# ADF032) was administered by RN and EMS was called. Client stated that it was difficult for her to swallow and that her headache was worsening. Client asked if she was on any medications for her blood pressure, which she stated she was on Amlodipine but that she was using it as recommended.    8:20 PM Client was complaining of worsening swelling, upon examination, swelling appeared to increase in the lips and throat. Stridor was noted upon auscultation, oxygen sat noted to be in the 80s. Client is lethargic and states that her ?legs feel weak.? Epinephrine pen (Lot # G210504X) 0.3 mg administered into the left thigh of the client. Fire Department arrived, client placed on oxygen via non-rebreather. EMS arrive shortly after and patient is moved to stretcher and per EMS is taken to the closest hospital (local) for further monitoring. Repeat VS at this time: HR 80, oxygen sat 100%, BP 225/109
Incorrect vaccine administered, parent informed. No adverse events at this time.

BRIEF OVERVIEW: Discharge Provider: PCP Primary Care Provider: None Physician, MD Admission Date: 11/29/2021 Discharge Date: Dec 2, 2021 DETAILS OF HOSPITAL STAY: PRESENTING PROBLEM: Suicidal thoughts [R45.851] Alcoholic intoxication without complication (HCC) [F10.920] Alcohol abuse with withdrawal (HCC) [F10.139] COVID-19 [U07.1] Nausea & vomiting [R11.2] HOSPITAL COURSE: 38-year-old male with a past medical history significant for alcohol abuse as well as history of alcohol withdrawal who presented to the ER due to concern for impending alcohol withdrawal and desire to undergo detox. In the emergency department the patient was found have a positive Breathalyzer test and have a positive serum ethanol level.  As he was slightly tachycardic he was given lorazepam per his request.  He had also reported at that time of some abdominal discomfort that had started earlier in the day and he also had a cough and complained of some shortness of breath despite being on room air.  Patient's lab testing was remarkable for mildly elevated liver enzymes as well as a positive COVID-19 PCR test.  Patient was thought to warrant admission to the hospital for observation. The patient was quickly discontinued from benzodiazepines as he had no overt signs of alcohol withdrawal.  He remained on room air throughout his hospital course.  Discussing with the patient, he stated that he was quite concerned about his nausea which he states he has had for some time he normally takes famotidine and Zofran at home.  His abdominal exam was benign and imaging in the form of CT of the abdomen pelvis was obtained which showed no acute pathology.  Patient's labs remained stable with a particularly stable hemoglobin.  At this point, getting nausea was uncertain but upon evaluating the patient throughout the day, he notably had spent the majority of his time sleeping and did not have any issues with nausea until he was woken up. After informing the patient that he appears to be medically stable for discharge from the hospital, he became quite concerned about his disposition plan as he stated that he was homeless and had no place to go.  Help ensure a stable/safe discharge plan, medical social work was involved and the patient was able to be discharged to a facility where he could stay in isolation due to his COVID-19 status.  He was continued on famotidine and Zofran involved discharge from the hospital 12/2.
OTHER_MEDS: famotidine (PEPCID) 20 MG tablet  ondansetron (ZOFRAN) 4 MG tablet
CUR_ILL: Multiple ER visits for alcohol intoxication prior to admission.

The 10mL ,  0.9%NS vial was disposed of at the end of each day. The patient did not experience any adverse reaction. At the recommendation of Pfizer and the CDC, due to lack of stability data, it was advised to revaccinate the patient.

I'm a very active, healthy 39 year old that works out typically 4-5 days a week, so this sudden urge to have to stop and catch my breathing isn't normal.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Since I have had adverse reactions to a vaccine before, I waited 30 minutes before leaving.  On the drive home, I began shivering and my left arm was throbbing.  When I got home, I pulled my short sleeve up and saw the injection area was swelling.  Under the band-aid, there was a small bruise, but I don't believe that had any impact on what was happening.  I took 600mg of Ibuprofen and grabbed an ice pack.  The shivering and cold I was feeling got progressively worse (omitting any impact the ice pack had, which was negligible).  I took my temperature around noon because I was still freezing under 2 pairs of leggings, undershirt, tee-shirt, sweatshirt, hat on my head, and a blanket.  My body temperature was in the low 96 range, verified by using 2 different oral and one ear thermometer.  ( I do not recall exactly, but I put that info in the vsafe app).  My arm continued to swell.  By the next day, it looked like someone put a ball under my skin, with surrounding areas swollen.  It was at least 3 inches in diameter.  When I lifted my arm, even the feel of fabric brushing the area caused increased pain.   I continued with the Ibuprofen and added zyrtec hoping it might help if there was any sort of allergic component.  The shivering continued and my low body temperature persisted for more than a week.  It took several weeks for my arm to heal.  It healed in time for dose 2 on Feb 9, but I was reluctant.  I spoke with some of the nurses there before agreeing to get dose 2.  One of them told me that the shivering was not uncommon, but she doubted many monitored  their  temperature like I did, and the swelling was not uncommon either.  I described as above, but she told me that the trend was that people who did not do that well with dose 1 (citing all of the people who were vaccinating for the county that had dose 2) did not have many complaints after dose 2.  They recommended I stick around for 45 minutes, which I did (since the last reaction began within 45 minutes).  Fearing I might lose use of my right arm (while I'm ambidextrous, my left hand writing has suffered as all of my work setup is geared toward right handed people), we used my left.  I showed the nurse where the first one was, so she moved the dose 2 site about 1.5".   I was fine after 45 minutes with only a mild swell, so they had me stick around another 15.  No change, so I went home.  Again, it was not nearly as bad as the first, but it was bad enough that I still needed Ibuprofen, ice packs, and had difficulty raising my arm at a 45 degree angle for several weeks.  The chills lasted only a few days and my temp was closer to normal (though I do not recall exactly).   Since the vaccines, I have had recurrent issues with my arm.   While not always having me think I needed to head to the doctor, I did schedule more than once, but cancelled because the pain resolved before I was seen several days later.  I occasionally get a "zap" in the area my arm swelled both times. Once, I was lifting a box ( I have had intermittent back issues, so I am VERY careful), and I felt the zap.  My right arm was fine.  My left swelled some and was sensitive to pressure for almost 2 weeks.  After a week and a half, I decided I needed to see the doctor, made the appointment, but cancelled the day before because there was nothing to see.  Many more instances since that are all similar.  I am currently about 5 days into the most recent issue.  I was pulling on our Christmas tree, trying to straighten it, and felt the zap.  Due to my angle, there was actually more tension on my right arm than left, and it is a 7.5' artificial tree, so not anything that was of significance.  This time, it is one of the "bad" ones, and I have made an appointment with my doctor.  I'm going to keep this one, regardless of if it feels fine or not.  As I type, I can feel a general ache and occasional more significant pain  that radiates up the muscle into my shoulder, then if I turn my head a bit left and slightly up, radiates up the left side of my neck about 2" from my spine.   Other general observations and info: 1.  While it was nameless to us, I had COVID in January 2020.  I barely moved for 8 days, had a 103.5 fever for 5, above 100 for 9 or 10 days, used my inhaler about every 4 hours, ached all over, and coughing.  I cannot recall everything because I slept for most of those days.  Not flu.  Just before feeling really sick, I noticed that my son's shoes didn't smell nearly as awful as they had ( strange statement, but true) and everyone thought I was crazy.  Then, I was cooking and was tasting the tacos and guacamole for seasoning.  It all tasted "off", so my daughter jumped in and finished.  To this day, avocados still have a more "earthy" taste, which is off from what I remember.  Most of my smell and taste came back by March/April.   2.  I did not feel back to "normal" energy-wise till April.   3.  Since the vaccine, my energy level is lower (not improving despite additional measures), I get more frequent migraines, and the issue with my arm is still problematic.
OTHER_MEDS: Adderall, Bupropion, Levothyroxine.  Took Ibuprofen for pain after vaccination.
HISTORY: Asthma, ADHD, Narcolepsy, some issues with my back.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient received a dose of Pfizer COVID-19Vaccine  Peds formulation (5-11yr) that may have been reconstituted with a single use vial of 0.9%NS that was entered into multiple times to reconstitute other vials of Pfizer vaccine. Staff did not realize the 10mL vial  was for single use only (to take out 1.3mL then discard). Each time the vial was used it was swabbed with alcohol and a new syringe was used to enter the vial then to add the diluent to the Pfizer vaccine for reconstitution. The 10mL ,  0.9%NS vial was disposed of at the end of each day. The patient did not experience any adverse reaction. At the recommendation of Pfizer and the CDC, due to lack of stability data, it was advised to revaccinate the patient.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient is a 92y.o. female who presented to the emergency department at hospital from senior living. At bedside, history taking from the patient is somewhat limited. I did contact senior living, and spoke with LPN for further information. LPN states that patient began to exhibit slurring of the speech, which began at approximately 7:30 AM on 11/7/21. She further states that her speech appeared somewhat slower than normal. LPN further states that patient administers her own medications, and doubts compliance. As well, it is noted that patient was found to have alcohol in her room. In addition, it appears that patient has oxycodone on her medication list.    The patient was noted to test positive for COVID-19 on 11/3/21, during routine testing. The patient was noted to be asymptomatic at the time. However, it is noted that patient frequently leaves the living facility, without utilization of mask. Patient COVID-19 vaccinated (Moderna - 2/29/21 and 1/22/21). The patient herself reports poor oral intake. She denies chest pain or shortness of breath, no addition to fevers or chills. Further denies diarrhea or abdominal pain. She does report right hip pain, however denies recent falls.    Her past medical history includes osteoarthritis of the right hip, aortic stenosis status post TAVR in 2018, sinus node dysfunction status post dual-chamber permanent pacemaker implantation, history of DVT in 2012, uterine carcinoma status post total abdominal hysterectomy with bilateral salpingo-oophorectomy in 2011 with subsequent completion of chemotherapy and XRT, impaired glucose tolerance, chronic bilateral lower extremity edema, essential hypertension, hypercholesterolemia, and a remote history of TIA. She is her own decision maker, as verified with LPN. The patient is not on home oxygen therapy.

Patient received his second Covid vaccination.  A few minutes later, patient state that "the shot felt different in my arm" and felt dizziness, nausea, and was pale in color.  At 1100, blood pressure was 141/82 P 58.  Offered a snack and water.  Patient sipped on cold water and refused offer of candy, peanut butter crackers, juice, and crackers.  Patient's mother states that he had a Propel drink this morning.  Patient transferred to cot with 2 assist and patient noted to have warm, clammy skin.  Cold cloth applied. Continued to observe patient.  At 1120, patient states that he feels weak and states that he has upper abdominal pain near his ribs.  BP, 121/74 P 53. Offered patient saltines and patient accepted.  Patient took bites of saltine when prompted by nurse.  At 1125, patient states that he feels slightly better and color pink. Mother states that he ate mozzarella sticks and chicken strips for supper last night after work but has not had anything else to eat since.  Mother states that he developed flu like symptoms after getting a flu shot when he was in kindergarten but no other problems with injections or vaccinations. Mother states that he does not take any medications and does not have any health issues.  At 1130, patient states that he feels about the same.  At 1136, patient states that "pain in striking my body" in different areas, including his left arm, stomach and stabbing pains in the left side of his chest. Patient pale.  At 1137, text sent to system. BP 117/74 P 59.  Patient states that he feels weak and left sided chest pain.  ANP responded with cardiology team for assessment. At 1140, BP 121/83 P 57.  Discussed transport to ED for further evaluation.  Patient states that he still feels weak.  Patient and mother okay for ambulance transport to ED.  911 contacted for ambulance transport at 1143.    IV of NS started in Left AC with 20 gauge angiocath on first attempt by cardiology nurse.  Patient left by EMS via stretcher.
LAB_DATA: 12/3/2021 Complete Blood Count, Basic Metabolic Panel, TSH, and Magnesium level drawn in ER.
PRIOR_VAX: Flu like symptoms (fever, lethargy) after receiving a flu shot at age 5.
